<title>Machaut: Loving Torment</title>
</head><body>
<h2>Machaut: Loving Torment</h2>

<dl>
<dt>L'amoureus tourment</dt>
<dd>Machaut et l'ancienne forge<br>
Marc Mauillon / Vivabiancaluna Biffi / Pierre Hamon<br>
<i>Eloquentia 0607</i></dd>
</dl>

<h3>Contents:</h3>
<p><ol>
<li>Machaut: Loyaut&eacute; que point ne delay</li>
<li>Anon., 15th c.: De cuer je soupire</li>
<li>Anon., Trouv&egrave;re: Lai de la Pastourelle</li>
<li>Lescurel: Comment que, pour l'&eacute;loignance</li>
<li>Machaut: Ay mi!</li>
</ol></p>

<p>Performers: Marc Mauillon (voice, bells), Vivabiancaluna Biffi
(vielle), Pierre Hamon (transverse flute, 3-hole flute, double
flute, cornemuse, drum, tambourine, direction)</p>

<p>Playing time: 55'</p>

<p>Recording date: November 2005 (Paris); released: 2006</p>

<p>Reviewed in:<br>
Diapason (#-p.): 541-94 (november 2006)<br>
Fanfare (Vol./#-p.): 34/1-326 (September/October 2010)<br>
Gramophone (Vol./#-p.): 84/1014-86 (january 2007)
</p>

<p><i>Loyaut&eacute; que point ne delay</i> is numbered as Machaut's
first lay, and is the only one to repeat the same music for each
stanza.  Here, the complete lyrics are recorded for the first time,
occupying most of the program.  Track #2 is the last surviving lay
of the medieval period.</p>

